snippet.textDisplay: There was a huge bump in Mercedes sales right after it won the 2014 F1 world championship. BMW likes to claim that they are the "sports" German brand yet they don't compete in any major motorsport series. For years Audi won Le Mans, now Mercedes is winning everything in Formula 1. BMW, nothing. These luxury car brands are not about practicality or reliability or usefulness or value. They are about emotion. They are about getting the consumer to feel "special" and "cool" about owning one of their cars, to make them feel like they're part of a winning team. The product almost doesn't really matter, it's all about evoking the emotion (Tesla being the perfect example). As long as BMW is not competing in any major motorsport series, it won't regain it's crown back.

snippet.textDisplay: BMW has dug itself a hole with poor reliability and excessively high repair costs compared to its competition. Example: mid-2000's 5-series involved in minor front-end collisions were frequently totaled by insurance companies because the cost to do repairs was so expensive. The VANOS variable-valve technology was known for its problems as well, which usually end in catastrophic engine failure. Electrical gremlins (aka 'parasitic power loss', or what most of us call 'a spontaneous dead battery') are still far more likely in a BMW than competing models. This last one was a big reason why my wife opted for a Mercedes over a BMW for her current car.
